Pattern 1: Rabin-Karp (The Rolling Hash)
This is the most intuitive of the three. Instead of comparing strings character by character, you compare their integer hashes.1. The ConceptIf you want to match a pattern of length $L$, calculate the hash of the pattern. Then, calculate the hash of the first $L$ characters of the text. As you slide the window across the text, drop the leftmost character from the hash and add the rightmost character.$$H_{new} = (H_{old} - \text{char}_{out} \times \text{base}^{L-1}) \times \text{base} + \text{char}_{in}$$2.

Java Blueprint
Java
public int rabinKarp(String text, String pattern) {
    if (pattern.length() > text.length()) return -1;
    
    int base = 256; // ASCII size
    int prime = 101; // A prime number for modulo to prevent overflow
    int m = pattern.length();
    int n = text.length();
    
    int patternHash = 0;
    int windowHash = 0;
    int h = 1;
    
    // The multiplier for the most significant digit: pow(base, m-1) % prime
    for (int i = 0; i < m - 1; i++) {
        h = (h * base) % prime;
    }
    
    // Calculate initial hashes
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        patternHash = (base * patternHash + pattern.charAt(i)) % prime;
        windowHash = (base * windowHash + text.charAt(i)) % prime;
    }
    
    // Slide the window
    for (int i = 0; i <= n - m; i++) {
        // If hashes match, verify characters to avoid collision false-positives
        if (patternHash == windowHash) {
            if (text.substring(i, i + m).equals(pattern)) return i;
        }
        
        // Calculate hash for next window
        if (i < n - m) {
            windowHash = (base * (windowHash - text.charAt(i) * h) + text.charAt(i + m)) % prime;
            if (windowHash < 0) windowHash += prime; // Fix negative modulos in Java
        }
    }
    return -1;
}

